<DocsLayout title="CLI Reference" description="lean-ctx v1.1.0 command-line interface — MCP server, shell hook, CLI commands, and persistent stats.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx is a single Rust binary that operates in multiple modes depending on the command-line arguments.
    In v1.1.0 it includes a full set of CLI commands alongside the MCP server and shell hook.
  </p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx [command] [options]</code></pre>

  <h2>Commands</h2>

  <h3>MCP Server (default, no args)</h3>
  <p>Starts the MCP server via stdio. This is the mode used by editors like Cursor, Claude Code, Copilot, and Windsurf.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>init</h3>
  <p>Initialize lean-ctx for the current project or globally. With <code>--global</code>, auto-installs shell aliases into your shell profile (<code>.zshrc</code> / <code>.bashrc</code>).</p>
  <pre><code># Project-local setup
lean-ctx init

# Global shell alias installation
lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>
  <p>
    The <code>--global</code> flag adds aliases for git, npm, cargo, docker, grep, find, ls, and curl
    so all CLI output is compressed transparently.
  </p>

  <h3>gain</h3>
  <p>Shows the persistent savings dashboard — cumulative token savings across all sessions. Stats are stored in <code>~/.lean-ctx/stats.json</code>.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx gain</code></pre>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx savings (all time)
══════════════════════════════════════════════════
Sessions: 47 | Total reads: 1,204 | Cache hits: 892 (74%)
Tokens saved: 2.4M | Cost avoided: $36.12
──────────────────────────────────────────────────
By Tool:
  ctx_read        812    1.8M    92%
  ctx_shell       284    480K    76%
  ctx_tree        108     89K    41%</code></pre>

  <h3>read</h3>
  <p>Read a file with lean-ctx compression directly from the terminal.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx read src/auth.ts
lean-ctx read src/auth.ts --mode map
lean-ctx read src/auth.ts --mode signatures</code></pre>

  <h3>diff</h3>
  <p>Compare two files and show a compressed diff.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx diff src/auth.ts src/auth.backup.ts</code></pre>

  <h3>grep</h3>
  <p>Compressed grep — searches for patterns and returns compact results.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx grep "createUser" src/</code></pre>

  <h3>find</h3>
  <p>Compressed find — locates files with token-efficient output.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx find "*.ts" src/</code></pre>

  <h3>ls</h3>
  <p>Compressed directory listing with indentation-based format.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx ls src/</code></pre>

  <h3>deps</h3>
  <p>Shows the dependency graph for a file — imports, exports, and connections.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx deps src/auth.ts</code></pre>

  <h3>Shell Hook: -c / exec</h3>
  <p>Execute a command and compress the output before printing.</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx -c git status
lean-ctx exec cargo build</code></pre>
  <p>Ideal for shell aliases (or use <code>lean-ctx init --global</code> to auto-install them):</p>
  <pre><code>alias git='lean-ctx -c git'
alias cargo='lean-ctx -c cargo'</code></pre>

  <h3>shell</h3>
  <p>Launch a shell wrapper that compresses all command output:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx shell
lean-ctx --shell</code></pre>
  <p>This starts a <code>lean-ctx></code> REPL that passes commands to the system shell and compresses output.</p>

  <h3>--version</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --version
# lean-ctx 1.1.0</code></pre>

  <h3>--help</h3>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --help</code></pre>

  <h2>Supported Shell Hook Patterns</h2>
  <p>The shell hook (via <code>-c</code>, <code>exec</code>, <code>shell</code>, or aliases) applies pattern-based compression for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>git</strong> — status, log, diff</li>
    <li><strong>npm</strong> — install, run, test</li>
    <li><strong>cargo</strong> — build, test, clippy</li>
    <li><strong>docker</strong> — build, ps</li>
    <li><strong>tsc</strong> — TypeScript compiler errors</li>
    <li><strong>grep</strong> — search results</li>
    <li><strong>find</strong> — file listings</li>
    <li><strong>ls</strong> — directory listings</li>
    <li><strong>curl</strong> — HTTP responses</li>
    <li><strong>test runners</strong> — jest, vitest, cargo test, pytest</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Unrecognized commands get generic compression: ANSI stripping, empty line removal, and long output truncation.</p>

  <h2>Persistent Stats</h2>
  <p>
    Starting with v1.1.0, lean-ctx tracks savings persistently in <code>~/.lean-ctx/stats.json</code>.
    Every MCP session and shell hook invocation contributes to the cumulative stats.
    Use <code>lean-ctx gain</code> to view the dashboard at any time.
  </p>

  <h2>Exit Codes</h2>
  <p>
    In shell hook mode (<code>-c</code>), lean-ctx forwards the exit code of the wrapped command.
    This ensures scripts and CI pipelines work correctly.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
